This question involves reasoning about one-dimensional and two-dimensional arrays of integers. You will write three static methods in a single enclosing class named `DiverseArray`.

Part (a): Write method `arraySum`, which returns the sum of the entries in a one-dimensional `int` array.

```java
/** Returns the sum of the entries in the one-dimensional array arr. */
public static int arraySum(int[] arr)
```

For example, if `arr1` contains `{1, 3, 2, 7, 3}`, then `arraySum(arr1)` returns `16`.

Part (b): Write method `rowSums`, which returns a one-dimensional array containing the sum of each row in a two-dimensional array.

```java
/** Returns a one-dimensional array in which each entry is the sum of
 *  the corresponding row in the two-dimensional array arr2D.
 */
public static int[] rowSums(int[][] arr2D)
```

Part (c): Write method `isDiverse`, which returns `true` if no two rows in `arr2D` have the same sum and returns `false` otherwise.

```java
/** Returns true if all rows in arr2D have different row sums;
 *  false otherwise.
 */
public static boolean isDiverse(int[][] arr2D)
```

rubric.reference_solution:
One acceptable implementation is:

```java
public static int arraySum(int[] arr)
{
  int sum = 0;
  for (int value : arr)
  {
    sum += value;
  }
  return sum;
}

public static int[] rowSums(int[][] arr2D)
{
  int[] sums = new int[arr2D.length];
  for (int row = 0; row < arr2D.length; row++)
  {
    sums[row] = arraySum(arr2D[row]);
  }
  return sums;
}

public static boolean isDiverse(int[][] arr2D)
{
  int[] sums = rowSums(arr2D);
  for (int j = 0; j < sums.length; j++)
  {
    for (int k = j + 1; k < sums.length; k++)
    {
      if (sums[j] == sums[k])
      {
        return false;
      }
    }
  }
  return true;
}
```

