Part (a): Write `getPeakIndex`. A peak is an element whose value is greater than the value immediately before it and greater than the value immediately after it. The method returns the index of the first peak found, or `-1` if no peak exists.

Examples:

| Array | `getPeakIndex` result |
|---|---:|
| `{11, 22, 33, 22, 11}` | `2` |
| `{11, 22, 11, 22, 11}` | `1` |
| `{11, 22, 33, 55, 77}` | `-1` |

Part (b): Write `isMountain`. The method should use `getPeakIndex`, `isIncreasing`, and `isDecreasing` to determine whether the array has the mountain property. An array with no peak is not a mountain.

rubric.reference_solution:
One acceptable implementation is:

```java
public static int getPeakIndex(int[] array)
{
  for (int k = 1; k < array.length - 1; k++)
  {
    if (array[k] > array[k - 1] && array[k] > array[k + 1])
    {
      return k;
    }
  }
  return -1;
}

public static boolean isMountain(int[] array)
{
  int peak = getPeakIndex(array);
  return peak != -1 &&
         isIncreasing(array, peak) &&
         isDecreasing(array, peak);
}
```

