This question involves reasoning about the GridWorld case study. A `Grub` is a `Critter` that chooses a direction, considers locations up to a maximum distance in that direction, and then selects a move location.

```java
public class Grub extends Critter
{
  private int maxDistance;

  public Grub(int distance)
  {
    maxDistance = distance;
  }

  public int getRandomDirection()
  {
    /* to be implemented in part (a) */
  }

  public ArrayList<Location> getMoveLocations()
  {
    /* to be implemented in part (b) */
  }

  public Location selectMoveLocation(ArrayList<Location> locs)
  {
    /* to be implemented in part (c) */
  }
}
```

Part (a): Write `getRandomDirection`, returning one of the eight direction constants from `Location`.

Part (b): Write `getMoveLocations`, returning all valid locations from one step through `maxDistance` steps away in a randomly selected direction. The method must not change the state of any actors.

Part (c): Write `selectMoveLocation`. If `locs` is empty, return the current location. Otherwise select a random location from `locs`. Return that location if it is empty or contains a `Flower`; return `null` if it contains any other actor.

rubric.reference_solution:
One acceptable implementation is:

```java
public int getRandomDirection()
{
  return Location.NORTH + (int) (Math.random() * 8) * Location.HALF_RIGHT;
}

public ArrayList<Location> getMoveLocations()
{
  ArrayList<Location> locs = new ArrayList<Location>();
  Grid<Actor> gr = getGrid();
  Location loc = getLocation();
  int dir = getRandomDirection();

  for (int k = 1; k <= maxDistance; k++)
  {
    Location next = loc.getAdjacentLocation(dir);
    if (gr.isValid(next))
    {
      locs.add(next);
      loc = next;
    }
  }
  return locs;
}

public Location selectMoveLocation(ArrayList<Location> locs)
{
  if (locs.size() == 0)
  {
    return getLocation();
  }
  Location loc = locs.get((int) (Math.random() * locs.size()));
  Actor actor = getGrid().get(loc);
  if (actor == null || actor instanceof Flower)
  {
    return loc;
  }
  return null;
}
```

