  {
    return score;
  }

  public int getFrequency()
  {
    return numStudents;
  }
}

public class Stats
{
  private ArrayList<ScoreInfo> scoreList;

  public boolean record(int score)
  {
    /* to be implemented in part (a) */
  }

  public void recordScores(int[] stuScores)
  {
    /* to be implemented in part (b) */
  }
}
```

The list `scoreList` is kept in increasing score order, and no two `ScoreInfo` objects contain the same score.

Part (a): Write `record`. If `score` is already represented in `scoreList`, increment that `ScoreInfo` object's frequency and return `false`. Otherwise insert a new `ScoreInfo` object in the correct sorted position and return `true`.

Part (b): Write `recordScores`, which records every score in `stuScores` by using `record`.

rubric.reference_solution:
One acceptable implementation is:

```java
public boolean record(int score)
{
  for (int k = 0; k < scoreList.size(); k++)
  {
    ScoreInfo info = scoreList.get(k);
    if (info.getScore() == score)
    {
      info.increment();
      return false;
    }
    if (score < info.getScore())
    {
      scoreList.add(k, new ScoreInfo(score));
      return true;
    }
  }
  scoreList.add(new ScoreInfo(score));
  return true;
}

public void recordScores(int[] stuScores)
{
  for (int score : stuScores)
  {
    record(score);
  }
}
```
